**PBM File Format**

You can almost directly write your ASCII art string into a PBM file.
Check the file format here: https://netpbm.sourceforge.net/doc/pbm.html

**Other file format**

If you prefer to create BMP | GIF | JPEG | PNG | TIFF | WBMP (the formats supported by [ImageIO][1]), follow this procedure:

 - First create a BufferedImage using it&#39;s [constructor][2].
 - Retrieve the [Graphics context][3] from the BufferedImage.
 - Draw your pixels into the Graphics context. 
   - Initialize the background using [setColor(Color.white)][4], [fillRect][5]. 
   - For each 1 draw a black rectangle: [setColor][4], [fillRect][5]
   You just have to count your bits so you know the coordinates of the rectagle.
 - Finally save the BufferedImage to file using [ImageIO.write()][6]

Converting from your ascii strings could look like this:

    Graphics g = ...
    // assuming your string values are stored in the array strings
    for(int y=0; y&lt;strings.length, y++) {
        String line = strings[y];
        for(int x=0; x&lt;line.length(); x++) {
            if (line.charAt(x)==&#39;1&#39;) {
                g.setColor(Color.black);
                g.fillRect(x, y, 1, 1);
            }
        }
    }


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.desktop/javax/imageio/package-summary.html
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.desktop/java/awt/image/BufferedImage.html#%3Cinit%3E(int,int,int)
  [3]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.desktop/java/awt/Graphics.html
  [4]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.desktop/java/awt/Graphics.html#setColor(java.awt.Color)
  [5]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/19/docs/api/java.desktop/java/awt/Graphics.html#fillRect(int,int,int,int)
  [6]: https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/17/docs/api/java.desktop/javax/imageio/ImageIO.html#write(java.awt.image.RenderedImage,java.lang.String,java.io.File)

