Here is another solution that should return all possible values of `x` and `y` which meet the criteria.
- I created lambdas for the generation and reversal processes.
- The generation lambda returns a string to avoid possible overflow when converting to an int.
- I use a `Set&lt;XY&gt;` of records to house the results in case there is more than one solution.  A class could also serve this purpose.
- This does not support negative values of `x` or `y`.

This uses two nested loops.  The first loop iterates forward on the ID while the nested loop iterates backwards on the starting at the end. If the id generated from those two values equals the source ID the values are stored in a record and added to a set.  When complete, the set is returned.
```
record XY(int x, int y) {}

BiFunction&lt;Integer, Integer, String&gt; getId = (a, b) -&gt; Integer.toString(a)
        + Integer.toString(a + b) + b;

Function&lt;String, Set&lt;XY&gt;&gt; reverse = (id) -&gt; {
     Set&lt;XY&gt; results = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();
     for (int i = 0; i &lt; id.length(); i++) {
         long first = Long.parseLong(id.substring(0, i + 1));
         for (int k = id.length() - 1; k &gt; i; k--) {
             long last = Long.parseLong(id.substring(k));
             if (getId.apply((int) first, (int) last).equals(id)) {
                 results.add(new XY((int) first, (int) last));
             }
         }
     }
     return results;
 };


Random r = new Random();
for (int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++) {
    int x = r.nextInt(100);
    int y = r.nextInt(200);
    String id = getId.apply(x,y);
    System.out.printf(&quot;%3d  %3d -&gt; %10s :  %s\n&quot;, x,y, id, 
       reverse.apply(id));
} 
  
